  • Set âExpirationâ to âNo expirationâ (see second picture below)

Connect github and an R-project

When you want to have an R-project connected to github, the workflow is like this:

  1. After logging into github click âNewâ on the top left (see first picture)

You can now âdo R stuffâ: Make changes like creating new files, code etc.

âCommitâ and âpushâ changes to github

Normally the files containing changes will appear in the âEnvironmentâ pane on the top right.

The very first time you push, youâll need to provide your PAT. There will be a popup window asking you how you want to identify yourself. Choose the last option and provide your PAT. If Iâm not mistaken you have to provide your PAT two times. After that it should be saved and you can commit and push without the need of identification.

Workflow and Troubleshooting

Recommended workflow

When working with R-projects that are connected to a github repo it makes sense to always:

  1. First âpullâ from the github repo right after starting RStudio.
    I (or other people) often worked on a project from another computer and the files on the computer I am working on currently were not up to date. If you pull first you make sure everything is up to date.
  2. Work on your project
  3. Commit and push everything at the end of the day (or working session).

âBut what if the github repo is behind and I âpullâ, wonât my newer local files be deleted?â
No.Â git knows that these files are ahead (newer) and wonât delete changes.

Can I connect existing projects to github?

My recommendation is always to first set up a github repo and then create an R-project. You can connect an already existing project to a github repo that you created afterward, but to be honest, itâs a pain.

Therefore, my recommendation for these cases is to create a github repo, then create a new R-project and simply copy your R-files from the old project to the new project. You can then commit and push the changes in the new R-project and voilÃ  the files are on github.
